[Details on the dead animals (including age, sex, breed, husbandry, nutritional situation, vaccination history) and on their population, e.g. the denominator (number of susceptible animals) and age distribution, will be helpful for the establishment of an hierarchical differential diagnosis list. In addition: Are animals of other species kept on the same premises? What is their respective health situation?

Sudden deaths in bovines could be caused by infectious agents (e.g. anthrax) as well as non-infectious agents (chemical and/or biological, such as poisonous plants and bio-toxins).

If/when anthrax is suspected, the traditional differential diagnosis would include grass tetany and thunderbolt.

"Corridor disease" (aka Theileriosis, East Coast fever) is a highly pathogenic disease of Cape buffaloes (_Syncerus caffer_) and cattle in eastern and southern Africa caused by the protozoan _Theileria parva lawrencei_, transmitted primarily by the tick _Rhipicephalus appendiculatus_; lesions and symptoms are similar to those of East Coast fever. It is one of 3 epidemiologically different diseases of which 3 different types of _T. parva_ are the respective causative agents; the other 2 are East Coast fever (ECF), caused by _T. p. parva_, and January disease, caused by _T. p. bovis_.

Observed pathological changes and results of lab investigations of the (apparently acute/per acute) deaths are anticipated. - Mod.AS

